Iya Ologi: I am afraid By Bashir Lucas Samson Lukman

https://knowislam.com.ng/iya-ologi-i-am-afraid-by-bashir-lucas-samson-lukman/

Iya Ologi - I Am Afraid

"Iya ologi", I called out to her
" kaaro sir" said she to me
The voice and greeting led me back to the days
Iya ologi would greet my father
Those days before he was bathed with dust

So, this greeting so familiar
Sermonizing and remindful
Today, I look so much like my father
I'm afraid, am I now a man?

Insooth, time has passed
The girl with a swollen chest calls me sir
And the broad-chested youth beckons at my call
Thirty kids on the streets call me Daddy
And to many, I have been 'Uncle-d'

This grey of mine I pluck
My delusion, it solemnly laughs
How soon has the child become an elder
And the son, the father of the man

Winters have besieged my brow
And is set to dig trenches on my comeliness
How soon shall I be wrinkled
And how many winters more shall I count

I have been deceived by the sluggishness of time
Suffice to call time a snailed-horse
Yesterday, I was a boy in his father's arms,
It is dawn, my beards have grown

As the days count, men get closer
And soon will man be bathed in dust
Delusion has no place and tomorrow in-non-existent
The child may have a thriftless hope in years to come
From whence comes the hope of the aged but foolery?

Iya Ologi has brought to me a reminder
Of the time gone and the age that has come
Where girls have become women
And men, now men of men

Shall we say time is a lightening
A flash or a mirage
All the treasure of our youthful days
Get laced on our own deep-sunken eyes

And the jester - African woman
We called and piped...
To our 'sin' she fumed
"Woman", we had called...
Now, the tune is changed
"lady" we called...
And with us, she merried and laughed
Lady she wants to be called, not woman
Albeit wrinkled - 40 winters have besieged her brow

I am afraid...
Each second brings one closer to the grave
Soon, shall we be long forgotten
Oh! Beloved shroud - we would be bathed in dust
Of the grave I am afeared...
Iya Ologi calls to rememberance...

Notes:

- Ogi/Akamu is called African corn pudding but Pizza is not oyinbo fufu

- Iya Ologi is a woman who sells Ogi

-  kaaro Ma (Yoruba language) means Good morning sir

In the heart of a bustling metropolis, nestled between towering steel and glass giants, existed a hidden haven known as Elmwood Park. Sunlight dappled through ancient oaks, dappling the emerald expanse with a mosaic of light and shadow. Laughter echoed through the park, carried on the gentle breeze along with the chirping of unseen birds. Children chased butterflies with gleeful abandon, their shouts mixing with the rhythmic clatter of squirrels gathering acorns.

On a weathered bench beneath a sprawling willow sat Beatrice, her silver hair shimmering like moonlight against the verdant backdrop. Her wrinkled hands held a worn leather book, its pages whispering tales of faraway lands and forgotten times. A mischievous grin flickered across her face as a curious ladybug landed on her open palm.

"Little one," she murmured, her voice warm and honeyed, "you seek adventure, do you not?" The ladybug seemed to pause, its tiny antennae twitching as if in understanding.

Meanwhile, on the other side of the park, a young boy named Leo navigated the intricate maze of a fallen log. His brown eyes sparkled with determination, his freckled nose crinkled in concentration. He imagined himself a fearless explorer, venturing into uncharted territories. Suddenly, a rustle in the nearby bushes startled him.

Emerging cautiously, Leo found himself face-to-face with a scruffy terrier, its tongue lolling out in a playful grin. Hesitantly, he extended a hand, and the dog nudged it with its wet nose. A friendship bloomed in that instant, their laughter echoing through the park, weaving a new melody into its symphony of sounds.

As the sun dipped below the horizon, casting long shadows across the grass, Beatrice closed her book with a sigh. The ladybug, as if sensing the shift in the day, took flight, soaring towards the last rays of golden light. Beatrice smiled, watching its tiny form disappear into the twilight.

"Remember," she whispered to the silent park, "the greatest adventures are often found in the smallest moments, in the connections we forge and the stories we share."

The park, as if acknowledging her words, hushed its symphony. The leaves rustled a gentle lullaby, the moon emerged like a watchful eye, and the city lights twinkled like distant stars. Beneath the cloak of night, Elmwood Park held its secrets close, waiting for the next dawn to bring new stories, new laughter, and new adventures.
